Format a USB
*************

Execute on the terminal:
lsblk

This will show you the connected disks. 
It will look like this : 

sda      8:0    0 512G  0 disk
├─sda1   8:1    0 500G  0 part
└─sda2   8:2    0  12G  0 part
sdb      8:16   1  16G  0 disk
└─sdb1   8:17   1  16G  0 part

if the usb is mounted you must unmount it*

sudo umount /dev/sdb1
(Replace sdb1 with the partition of your usb)*

If you have a lot of partitions: *
sudo umount /dev/sdb*


Now, format the USB: 
* FAT32 ( compatible with Windows, Mac, Linux )
sudo mkfs.vfat -F 32 /dev/sdb1

* exFAT (it's best for large archives)
sudo mkfs.exfat /dev/sdb1

*EXT4 (only for Linux)
sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1


NTFS:
follow the steps but use this instead
sudo mkfs.ntfs -f -L MI_USB /dev/sdb1
